Neodymium: China controls rare earth used in phones, electric cars|http://www.cnbc.com/john-harwood|http://www.cnbc.com/video/2018/10/19/neodymium-china-controls-rare-earth-used-in-phones-electric-cars.html||2018-10-19|Nelson Ching,Bloomberg,Getty Images||Tesla Model 3 and other electric cars are driving up demand for a metal called neodymium and China controls the world&#39;s supply

7:30 AM ET Fri, 19 Oct 2018

Powerful magnets are necessary for an iPhone to vibrate or a Tesla Model 3&#39;s motor to spin. If you combine neodymium with iron and boron, you can make a neodymium-iron-boron magnet, which is the most powerful type of permanent magnet ever created. And demand for these magnets is on the rise. But 80 percent of the world&#39;s neodymium comes from China.
